<item>
            <title>[DATAMONGO-584] Add support for MongoDB 2.10.0 driver and the newly introduced MongoClient API</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATAMONGO-584</link>
                <project id="10701" key="DATAMONGO">Spring Data MongoDB</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The 2.10.0 version of the MongoDB Java driver introduces a new &lt;tt&gt;MongoClient&lt;/tt&gt; API that changes the default behavior to be more safe (similar to &lt;tt&gt;WriteConcern.SAFE&lt;/tt&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&apos;re planning to adapt these to changes in the following way:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Check for the presence of the new driver through a class loading check&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Use &lt;tt&gt;MongoClient&lt;/tt&gt; instead of &lt;tt&gt;Mongo&lt;/tt&gt; by default if we are on driver 2.10.0&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Continue to use &lt;tt&gt;Mongo&lt;/tt&gt; if we&apos;re on drivers &amp;lt; 2.10.0&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;This transparently changes the default write-concern checks under the covers which might not be expected. But as it is &quot;just safer&quot; essentially and we&apos;re not risking unintended data loss, it&apos;s worth to move to the new functionality.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For more details on the driver API changes see &lt;a href=&quot;http://docs.mongodb.org/manual/release-notes/drivers-write-concern/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://docs.mongodb.org/manual/release-notes/drivers-write-concern/&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
